Date: 0/0/1898
Source: Merriam-Webster Third International
Author:
Vol / Page: 2017
Edition:
Quote: A'.ke (a.'.k&amacr.; colloq. a.'.ke.) } n. A'.ke-a'.ke (a.'.k&amacr.-a.'.k&amacr.; colloq. often&abreve.k'.e.-&abreve.k'.), } [Maori.] [The reduplicated form is more common.]  (Bot.) A sapindaceous tree (Dodonaea viscosa) of New Zealand, one of the hop bushes. See under HOP. The name ake-ake is also given to two composite trees (Olearia avicennifolia and O. Traversii). [Local, N.Z.]
